"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1samuel-19-21.py

Ch 19: Jonathan mediates; Michal helps David escape; Naioth prophetic community protects David.
Ch 20: Jonathan-David covenant; new moon festival; arrow signal; farewell.
Ch 21: David at Nob; showbread; Goliath's sword; Doeg; David feigns madness at Gath.

Context focus: prophetic communities in early Israel, teraphim archaeology, new moon festivals,
showbread legislation, Nob as priestly city, Achish of Gath as historical figure, ANE feigned madness.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(type_, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(type_, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

CONTEXT = {
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>Saul's explicit order to kill David marks the transition from covert attempts (the spear-throwings of 18:11; 19:10) to open assassination command. Jonathan and all Saul's servants are ordered to act against David. The politicization of the court against a military hero who has done nothing disloyal reflects a pattern well-documented in ANE court histories: rulers who perceived rising rivals often mobilized the court structure as an elimination mechanism before the rival was strong enough to resist.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jonathan warns David privately. Jonathan's position as crown prince who is actively protecting his father's rival reflects the complexity of competing loyalties in a household-based political system. In the patrimonial kingdoms of Iron Age I Palestine, loyalty ran simultaneously to family, tribe, king, and covenant — Jonathan's covenant with David (18:3) created an obligation that competed with filial loyalty. His warning to David is not treason but covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jonathan proposes that David hide in the field while Jonathan speaks with his father. The 'field' here is likely the agricultural land outside Gibeah — an easily accessible hiding place where David can hear the conversation or receive a quick report. Jonathan's plan is diplomatic: he will probe Saul's intentions and report to David, allowing David to either return safely or remain hidden based on the outcome.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jonathan intercedes for David before his father, citing David's military service and the Goliath victory: 'Let not the king sin against his servant David, for he has not sinned against you, and his deeds have been very good toward you.' The phrase 'sin against his servant' (<em>yehĕṭāʾ hammelek bəʿaḇdô</em>) is covenant language — Jonathan frames the potential murder as a covenant violation, not merely a political miscalculation. Killing someone who has acted loyally is a breach of patronage obligations.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jonathan recalls David's act on Israel's behalf against Goliath: 'He took his life in his hand and struck down the Philistine, and YHWH worked a great salvation for all Israel.' The appeal to YHWH's involvement in the Goliath victory is Jonathan's theological argument: if YHWH used David to save Israel, moving against David means moving against YHWH's instrument. This is the same logic David will use with Saul directly in 24:11-13.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Saul heeds Jonathan's voice and swears: 'As YHWH lives, he shall not be put to death.' The oath in YHWH's name creates a formal covenant commitment. Oaths by a deity's life were among the most binding forms of promise in the ancient world — breaking such an oath was an act against the deity invoked. Saul's oath will be violated within days (vv9-10), which in itself constitutes a religious as well as political transgression.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jonathan brings David back to Saul, and David serves Saul as before. The restoration is complete on the surface but structurally temporary. The evil spirit from YHWH (19:9) will return; the same pattern that produced the spear-throwing of 18:10-11 is not cured by an oath. The chapter's rapid oscillation between Saul's moments of clarity and his descents into violence mirrors the psychological portrait of a man with a fragmented will.</p>",
    "8": "<p>War breaks out again and David strikes the Philistines with great force so that they flee before him. David's military success continues unabated — his victories are the very events that trigger Saul's jealousy cycle. The connection between military success and Saul's deterioration is the narrative's implicit argument: YHWH's blessing on David (18:14) produces the victories that produce the jealousy that produces the violence. The blessing cannot be hidden.</p>",
    "9": "<p>An evil spirit from YHWH comes upon Saul as he sits in his house with his spear. David is playing music — the same therapeutic role that brought him into Saul's service initially (16:23). The juxtaposition is pointed: David playing for Saul's relief, Saul sitting with a weapon ready. The 'evil spirit from YHWH' (<em>rûaḥ rāʿāh mēʾiṯ YHWH</em>) — YHWH's withdrawal of protection producing psychological deterioration — is not demon possession in the later sense but divine judicial abandonment. The spear in Saul's hand at a musical performance is not hunting equipment; it is a court weapon kept for protection, now weaponized against his own court musician.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Saul attempts to pin David to the wall with the spear — the third spear-attack (cf. 18:11 twice). David dodges and the spear strikes the wall. He flees and escapes that night. The nightly flight distinguishes this episode from the earlier attacks: Saul's violence has now extended to follow David after the musical session, creating a mortal threat that cannot be managed by music or by Jonathan's mediation. David must leave.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Saul sends messengers to David's house to watch him and kill him in the morning. The night surveillance against dawn execution was a known tactic in ANE political assassination — killing at night risked blood-guilt complications, but execution at dawn after a formal 'discovery' could be framed more defensibly. Michal, David's wife and Saul's daughter, sees the agents and warns David.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Michal lets David down through a window. The domestic architecture of Iron Age Israelite houses typically included windows facing outside the city wall — the story echoes Rahab's lowering of the spies through a window in Jericho (Josh 2:15) and anticipates later escapes through windows in Acts 9:25 (Paul's escape from Damascus). The window escape is the private counterpart to the public city-gate: the usual means of entry and exit bypassed by subversion.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Michal places the <em>tərāpîm</em> (household idol) in the bed, puts a goat-hair pillow at its head, and covers it with a garment. The presence of <em>tərāpîm</em> in the household of David and Saul's daughter is archaeologically significant. Teraphim were small human-shaped figurines used in household religion throughout the Iron Age — found in excavations across Judah and Israel. Their presence in the household of the king's daughter does not indicate explicit idolatry but reflects the layered religious practice of the period, where YHWH worship coexisted with household cult objects (cf. Rachel's theft of Laban's teraphim, Gen 31:19).</p>",
    "14": "<p>When Saul's messengers come for David, Michal says he is sick. The deception buys time by invoking a plausible domestic situation — illness confined to bed was impossible to verify quickly through a closed door. Saul, unwilling to wait for a natural death, sends the messengers back to bring David on his bed so he can kill him. The escalation from 'wait' to 'bring the bed' shows Saul's impatience overcoming his concern for procedure.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Saul says: 'Bring him up to me in the bed, that I may kill him.' The command to bring a sick man on his bed is an almost burlesque escalation — Saul is so determined that he will kill a supposed invalid in his sickbed. When the messengers find only the teraphim, the deception is exposed.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The messengers find the teraphim with the goat-hair pillow. The double layer of the deception — the mannequin (teraphim) plus the realistic hair-pillow — reflects Michal's ingenuity. The goat-hair pillow specifically was used in burial practice across the ancient Near East; the combination of the prone figure with the hair-covering may have created a convincing death-sick appearance.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Saul confronts Michal: 'Why have you deceived me like this and let my enemy go, so that he has escaped?' Michal's response shifts blame to David — she claims David threatened her life if she did not help. Whether Michal's claim was true or a self-protective lie, the narrative does not adjudicate. The episode demonstrates that Saul's surveillance state has fractured even family loyalty: daughter is willing to deceive father, or alternatively, husband threatened wife. Neither reading honors the household.</p>",
    "18": "<p>David flees to Samuel at Ramah and tells him everything Saul had done to him. Samuel and David go to Naioth in Ramah. <em>Nāweh</em> or Naioth means 'dwellings' or 'habitations' and apparently describes a prophetic community — a communal living arrangement for the sons of the prophets (<em>bənê hannəḇîʾîm</em>). These prophetic guilds, also associated with Elijah and Elisha (2 Kings 2:3-5; 4:38-44), were semi-monastic communities that gathered around a master prophet. Ramah's Naioth is the oldest such community mentioned by name.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Saul is told that David is at Naioth in Ramah. The intelligence network that traced David to Nob (21:7) and to Jonathan's meetings is now locating him at the prophetic community. The extension of Saul's surveillance into sacred space — hunting David within a prophetic community gathered around Samuel — is the chapter's final escalation.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Saul sends messengers to seize David, and they encounter the company of prophets prophesying with Samuel standing over them — the Spirit of God comes on the messengers and they prophesy too. The prophetic contagion that overcomes Saul's agents reflects the understanding of Spirit-empowered prophecy in early Israel as something that could spread involuntarily through proximity. Saul's agents are not converted; they are simply overpowered by the Spirit's presence, unable to complete their mission.</p>",
    "21": "<p>This happens to a second and third set of messengers. The triple repetition — three groups of agents, each overcome by the prophetic Spirit — is a formal narrative pattern establishing the completeness and inescapability of the divine protection. Saul's messengers are not defeated by military force but by the same Spirit that had once come on Saul himself (10:6-10). The contrast with his current condition is pointed.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Saul goes to Secu and asks where Samuel and David are. He is told they are at Naioth in Ramah. Secu is an otherwise unknown location near Ramah — a cistern site where Saul makes inquiries. His personal descent into the region of Samuel's prophetic community represents an escalation beyond sending agents.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Spirit of God comes on Saul as he travels, and he prophesies all the way to Naioth in Ramah. Unlike his messengers who prophesied and stopped, Saul prophesies continuously on the journey — the Spirit overwhelming his mission before he even arrives. The geography of the Spirit overcoming Saul progressively from Secu to Naioth narrates the shrinking of Saul's autonomous agency under divine constraint.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Saul strips off his robes and prophesies before Samuel, lying naked all that day and night. Hence the proverb: 'Is Saul also among the prophets?' (cf. 10:12). Stripping garments in a prophetic state was an ecstatic practice — Isaiah walked naked and barefoot for three years as a prophetic sign (Isa 20:2-3). Saul's public nakedness before Samuel is the humiliation of the king's dignity by the same Spirit he once received: he cannot harm David because he cannot stop prophesying. The narrative is darkly comic — the king who came to kill is prostrated in ecstatic worship.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>David flees from Naioth in Ramah and comes to Jonathan, asking: 'What have I done? What is my sin against your father, that he seeks my life?' The question is genuine — David does not know what specific act triggered the latest assault. His appeal to Jonathan reflects the covenant they share: Jonathan is both the one who can intercede with Saul and the one who knows Saul's inner state.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jonathan's response reflects incomplete information: 'You shall not die. My father does nothing without disclosing it to me. Why should my father hide this from me? It is not so.' Jonathan believes he is in Saul's confidence. His assumption — that Saul would have told him about any serious plan against David — reflects the normal expectation of a crown prince's access to royal decision-making. He is wrong, and David knows it.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David swears: 'Your father knows well that I have found favor in your eyes, and he thinks, Do not let Jonathan know this, lest he be grieved. But truly, as YHWH lives and as you live, there is but a step between me and death.' The phrase 'a step between me and death' (<em>kəpeṣaʿ bênî ûḇên hammāweṯ</em>) became a proverbial expression of mortal danger. David's assessment is accurate: he is not catastrophizing but calculating.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jonathan offers David whatever he wants. The offer reflects the latitude Jonathan has as crown prince — he can act on David's behalf in ways a lower-ranking person could not. The covenant between them creates a mutual obligation structure: David's request will come with a corresponding pledge.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David proposes the new moon festival test. The new moon (<em>ḥōḏeš</em>) was a significant monthly festival in ancient Israel requiring the sounding of trumpets, special sacrifices, and, in the court context, a formal meal at the king's table (Num 10:10; 28:11-15). David's absence from the new moon feast would be conspicuous — a court official's failure to attend was either a medical emergency or a political signal. The king's reaction to David's absence would reveal his intent.</p>",
    "6": "<p>David's cover story: if Saul asks, Jonathan is to say David requested to go to Bethlehem for the family's annual sacrifice. The annual family sacrifice at Bethlehem is a plausible claim — local religious festivals at ancestral sites were normal practice. Jesse's family in Bethlehem would have an annual commemoration around the new moon or a specified religious festival. The story is credible enough to require Saul to choose between accepting it and revealing his hand.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'If he says, Good, your servant is well; but if he is angry, then know that harm is determined by him.' David's request is for a binary diagnostic: Saul's reaction to a credible excuse will reveal his pre-decided intentions. If Saul accepts the excuse, David's position may be recoverable; if Saul's anger flares regardless, his intention is certain. This is the same empirical-test logic the Philistine priests applied to the ark-return (6:9).</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Show covenant loyalty (<em>ḥesed</em>) to your servant, for you have brought your servant into a covenant of YHWH with you.' David invokes the specific covenant term <em>ḥesed</em> — loyalty, steadfast love, the covenant quality of faithfulness to obligations. He situates the test within their formal covenant relationship: Jonathan owes David covenant loyalty because they have formally bound themselves to each other before YHWH. The appeal is legal, not merely emotional.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jonathan assures David that if he knew his father intended harm, he would tell him. The covenant-friendship here is reciprocal: Jonathan is not merely acting as a favor to David but fulfilling obligations he has voluntarily undertaken. His assurance — 'the LORD do so to Jonathan and more also if it please my father to do you harm, and I do not disclose it to you' — is a self-imprecatory oath, the strongest form of commitment available.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David asks: 'Who will tell me if your father answers harshly?' The practical question is how to communicate the outcome securely. A direct face-to-face meeting after the new moon would be dangerous if Saul intends harm. The arrow-signal system (vv35-40) is Jonathan's solution — a covert communication method that looks like a training exercise.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jonathan takes David out into the field. The field setting for covenant-making is a liminal space — away from walls that could have ears, outside the domestic and political structures. The covenant they are about to renew was originally made in 18:3 and renewed in 23:18; this is the fullest articulation of its terms.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jonathan invokes YHWH as witness: 'YHWH, God of Israel! When I have sounded out my father, about this time tomorrow or the third day, behold, if he is well disposed toward David, shall I not then send to you and disclose it to you?' The divine witness to the covenant communication plan is the formal covenant structure: YHWH will hold Jonathan accountable to deliver the message faithfully.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'But should it please my father to do you harm, the LORD do so to Jonathan and more also if I do not disclose it to you and send you away, that you may go in safety. May YHWH be with you, as he has been with my father.' Jonathan's farewell blessing — 'may YHWH be with you as he has been with my father' — is a remarkable acknowledgment: Jonathan already knows that YHWH is departing from his father and going with David. The blessing passes YHWH's presence from the Saulide line to David.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jonathan asks David to show him <em>ḥesed YHWH</em> — YHWH-quality covenant loyalty — if David is still alive when YHWH cuts off David's enemies. The request anticipates David's eventual kingship and Jonathan's either death or subordination. Jonathan is negotiating the terms of David's future treatment of his descendants from a position of vulnerability, acknowledging that dynastic transitions in the ANE typically involved elimination of the former dynasty's heirs.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'And do not cut off your covenant loyalty from my house forever, even when YHWH cuts off every one of the enemies of David from the face of the earth.' Jonathan uses the language of cutting off (<em>kāraṯ</em>) — the same term used for covenant-making ('cutting a covenant') — and applies it to his own potential fate. The covenant he has cut with David is the guarantee against the cutting off his descendants might otherwise face. This covenant will be fulfilled in David's treatment of Mephibosheth (2 Sam 9).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Jonathan cuts a covenant with the house of David. The formal covenant act creates a legally binding obligation on David and his successors toward Jonathan's descendants. The covenant is with the house of David (not just David personally) — it extends across generations, acknowledging that Jonathan's children will be alive in David's kingdom long after both men are dead.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Jonathan makes David swear again in his love for him — 'for he loved him as he loved his own soul' (<em>kəʾahaḇaṯ napšô</em>). The renewal of the oath in the context of love is the emotional core of what has been legally structured in the preceding verses. The covenant is not a cold contract but a formalization of genuine friendship of the deepest ANE kind — the love that exceeds self-interest.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jonathan sets out the arrow-signal plan for communicating after the new moon. 'You will be missed because your seat will be empty.' The social significance of the empty seat in court — an assigned position at the royal table whose absence is both visually and politically conspicuous — is the mechanism of the test. Presence at the royal table was both an honor and an obligation for court officials.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jonathan instructs David to go to the place where he hid on the day of the matter and stay beside the stone Ezel. The stone Ezel is an apparently known landmark near Gibeah, mentioned only here. The specificity of the hiding place — the same place used during a previous emergency — suggests an established pattern of covert meeting, consistent with the secret nature of the Jonathan-David relationship under Saul's surveillance.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Jonathan's arrow signal: he will shoot three arrows to the side of the stone as if shooting at a mark. The use of archery practice as a cover for the signal is practical intelligence tradecraft — it provides a visible and plausible reason for being in the field with a servant, while the actual message is encoded in the directional command given to the servant.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'If I say to the boy, Look, the arrows are on this side of you, take them — then you are to come, for it is safe for you and there is no danger, as YHWH lives.' The 'come' signal is the favorable response: David can safely return to Gibeah. The invocation of YHWH even for the signal phrase — 'as YHWH lives' — grounds the communication system in covenant reliability.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'But if I say to the boy, Look, the arrows are beyond you — then go, for YHWH has sent you away.' The 'beyond' signal means flight is necessary. Jonathan frames even the negative outcome as YHWH's action: 'YHWH has sent you away.' Whether the news is stay or go, Jonathan situates it within divine providence. The covenant between them has YHWH as its guarantor and interpreter.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'And as for the matter of which you and I have spoken, behold, YHWH is between you and me forever.' The covenant's ultimate grounding is YHWH's permanent witness. The phrase '<em>YHWH bênî ûḇêneḵā ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em>' — YHWH between you and me forever — is the covenant's theological capstone: it transcends the immediate crisis, their lifetimes, and extends to their descendants (cf. v14-15).</p>",
    "24": "<p>David hides in the field. At the new moon Saul sits at the feast to eat, seated at his usual place against the wall — the king's position with his back protected. Jonathan sits opposite and Abner, Saul's commander, beside Saul. David's place is empty. The meal scene is carefully rendered: the exact positions of the diners are noted, making David's absence conspicuous by its specificity.</p>",
    "25": "<p>On the first day Saul says nothing. The silence is strategic — Saul may be giving David one day's grace, or he may be calculating. The text only records that he thought 'Something has happened to him; he is not clean, surely he is not clean.' Ritual uncleanness (<em>ṭumʾāh</em>) from nocturnal emission or contact with a corpse was a legitimate reason for missing a cultic meal (Lev 15:16-18). Saul's first assumption is generous or at least plausible.</p>",
    "26": "<p>This verse records Saul's first-day silence. His initial assumption of ritual uncleanness is the most charitable available interpretation of David's absence. The cultic calendar and purity requirements provided a ready-made cover for absences that might otherwise be suspicious — Saul's invocation of it suggests either genuine consideration or a one-day grace period before pressing the matter.</p>",
    "27": "<p>On the second day — when David's place is again empty — Saul asks Jonathan directly why Jesse's son has not come to the feast 'yesterday or today.' The phrase 'Jesse's son' rather than 'David' is Saul's distancing language — he uses the patronymic to signal that David is not in his estimation a member of the court family but an outsider whose absence is a political statement.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Jonathan delivers the cover story: David urgently requested to go to his family's sacrifice in Bethlehem at his brother's command. The elaboration — 'commanded by my brother' — adds familial authority to the request, making it appear that David had no choice but to comply. The story is plausible and specific enough that Saul must either accept it or reveal that he has pre-decided to harm David regardless of the explanation.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Please let me go, for our clan holds a sacrifice in the city, and my brother has commanded me to be there.' The appeal to family obligation and prior commitment is designed to be unassailable within the honor-culture of Iron Age Israel: refusing a family sacrificial command from an elder brother would be a social offense. Saul's reaction will reveal whether he accepts the cultural logic or is operating outside it.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Saul's anger flares against Jonathan: 'You son of a perverse and rebellious woman!' The social insult — directed at Jonathan's mother rather than at Jonathan himself — is the ANE equivalent of the most severe personal attack. Insulting a man through his mother's virtue and loyalty was among the worst forms of verbal aggression in ancient Near Eastern cultures, documented in both Mesopotamian and Ugaritic texts. Saul's rage bypasses rational argument and goes directly to social humiliation.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'For as long as Jesse's son lives on the earth, neither you nor your kingship will be established.' Saul's explicit statement reveals what he has known and feared: Jonathan's kingship succession depends on David's elimination. Saul has recognized the threat to his dynasty's future that David represents — not because David is actively plotting against it, but because YHWH's designation of David has created an alternative dynastic claim that Saul cannot eliminate through normal political means.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Jonathan protests: 'Why should he be put to death? What has he done?' Jonathan continues to argue David's innocence — the same argument he made in 19:4-5. His persistence in defending David even under direct royal anger demonstrates the depth of his covenant commitment.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Saul hurls his spear at Jonathan to strike him — the same violent reaction he had toward David (18:11; 19:10). The spear-throw at his own son is the chapter's decisive moment: Saul has now crossed the line from political violence against a rival to familial violence against his heir. Jonathan knows from this that Saul 'was determined to kill David' — the resolution is definitive, not conditional.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Jonathan rises from the table in fierce anger and eats nothing on the second day of the new moon. He is grieved for David because his father had shamed him. Jonathan's grief is double: the covenant relationship with David is severed by his father's decision, and the shaming of Jonathan himself (the spear-throw in public) is a political and personal humiliation. He fasts involuntarily from grief.</p>",
    "35": "<p>In the morning Jonathan goes out to the field for the appointed signal, and a small boy is with him. The elaborate preparation for a simple message — a boy, arrows, a designated field — is the intelligence operation's final execution. The boy is a cover; the arrows are the medium; the directional command is the message.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Jonathan says to the boy: 'Run and find the arrows that I shoot.' As the boy runs, Jonathan shoots an arrow beyond him. The 'beyond' placement of the arrow is the dangerous-departure signal. The boy runs to the arrow's location without understanding the significance of where Jonathan shot.</p>",
    "37": "<p>When the boy comes to where Jonathan's arrow fell, Jonathan calls after the boy: 'Is not the arrow beyond you?' The question encodes the message; David, hidden among the rocks nearby, hears it and understands. The signal system works precisely as designed: the servant receives the surface instruction; David receives the covert message.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Jonathan calls after the boy: 'Hurry, be quick, do not stay.' The urgency of the additional commands — beyond what was needed for simple arrow-retrieval — reinforces the departure signal. Jonathan is pressing the message through the surface action.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The boy knows nothing. Only Jonathan and David understood the matter. The narrative's note about the servant's ignorance confirms the system's security: the covert communication remained concealed even from the immediate participant. This is the characteristic of a well-designed signal system.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Jonathan gives his weapons to the boy and sends him into the city. The sending away of the servant creates privacy for the farewell. Without the witness, the covenant friends can drop the cover and speak plainly. Jonathan's weapons — the bow and arrows just used in the signal — are sent away as if the training exercise is complete.</p>",
    "41": "<p>As soon as the boy is gone, David comes out from beside the south stone, falls on his face and bows three times. Then they kiss each other and weep together, David weeping the most. The formal greeting (prostration and bowing) followed by kissing and weeping is the full social-emotional range of the ANE farewell — the prostration honors the covenant superior (Jonathan as crown prince), the kiss seals the covenant bond, and the weeping acknowledges the finality of the parting. This is the last time they will see each other alive.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Jonathan says: 'Go in peace, because we have sworn both of us in the name of YHWH, saying, YHWH shall be between me and you, and between my offspring and your offspring, forever.' Jonathan's final words are not personal sentiment but covenantal declaration — the covenant itself, with its trans-generational scope, is his farewell gift. David then rises and leaves, and Jonathan goes into the city. The men depart in opposite directions; the narrative has given them everything but proximity.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>David comes to Nob (<em>nōḇ</em>), the priestly city, to Ahimelech the priest. Ahimelech comes out trembling (<em>ḥāraḏ</em>) to meet David — his fear signals that David's arrival without a military escort or royal commission is unusual and alarming. Nob is identified with the ridge northeast of Jerusalem, visible from the city (Isa 10:32 describes an Assyrian army shaking its fist at Nob, visible from the approach to Jerusalem). The city housed the displaced priestly community after Shiloh's destruction.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David gives a cover story: he is on a secret royal mission and has arranged to meet his men at a designated place. The fabrication is necessary for Ahimelech's protection — if Ahimelech knows David is a fugitive, any assistance he provides constitutes harboring. David's deception protects the priest by limiting his culpable knowledge. The tragic irony is that Doeg the Edomite is already present (v7), making the deception ultimately fatal for Ahimelech.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David asks for bread — 'five loaves or whatever is here.' The quantity (five loaves) reflects the scale of a small group's immediate need. The 'whatever is here' suggests he is not demanding but requesting whatever is available. In Hebrew hospitality culture, providing food for travelers was a social obligation; Ahimelech's concern is not about generosity but about the sacred status of what he has available.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ahimelech says he has no ordinary (<em>ḥōl</em>) bread — only the bread of the Presence (<em>leḥem happānîm</em>), the showbread that sits before YHWH on the table in the sanctuary. The showbread consisted of twelve loaves arranged in two rows of six on a gold table in the Holy Place, renewed each Sabbath. Leviticus 24:5-9 specifies that the old loaves were reserved for Aaron and his sons to eat in the sanctuary. Giving this bread to David would be a deviation from its prescribed sacred use — but Ahimelech is willing to consider it if the men are ritually qualified.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ahimelech's condition: the men must have 'kept themselves from women' (<em>šāmrû minnāšîm</em>) — the ritual sexual abstinence required of warriors in holy war (cf. Deut 23:9-14; 2 Sam 11:11 where Uriah refuses to sleep with his wife because of the sacred war context). David assures him the men have been ritually pure for three days. The priest's question treats David's reported mission as a sacred-war context in which the showbread's use could be authorized by emergency necessity.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Ahimelech gives David the bread of the Presence that was removed from before YHWH to be replaced by fresh bread that day — it was the Sabbath and fresh loaves had just been set out. The timing detail — the old loaves being removed exactly when David arrived — is either providential coincidence or narrative tidiness. The showbread had completed its week before YHWH; the old loaves were being returned to priestly use; David receives them in the moment of transition.</p>",
    "7": "<p>On that day a servant of Saul was detained before YHWH (<em>neʿĕṣār lipnê YHWH</em>) — Doeg the Edomite, the chief of Saul's shepherds. The phrase 'detained before YHWH' likely refers to a period of ritual fulfillment at the sanctuary — perhaps fulfilling a vow or completing a period of purification that required remaining at the sanctuary. Doeg's presence is incidental, not investigative, but it makes him a witness to everything that follows.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David asks if there is a spear or sword available — he came in such haste he brought no weapon. The absence of a personal weapon underscores the emergency nature of his departure from Gibeah: David left quickly with nothing, making the trip to Nob necessary for basic equipment. A court warrior who appears at a sanctuary without a weapon is conspicuously under-equipped.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ahimelech tells David that the sword of Goliath the Philistine — the one David struck down in the Valley of Elah — is here, wrapped in a cloth behind the ephod. If David wants it, he may take it; there is no other. The storage of Goliath's sword as a trophy at the sanctuary is consistent with ANE practice of depositing significant war spoils at temples — the sword that YHWH gave David victory with belongs in YHWH's sanctuary. David accepts it: 'There is none like it; give it to me.'</p>",
    "10": "<p>David rises and flees from Saul and comes to Achish the king of Gath. Achish of Gath appears in later narratives as a Philistine ruler who eventually becomes David's patron (chs 27-29). The Amarna letters and various ANE sources identify Gath (Tell es-Safi/Tel Zafit) as a significant Philistine city-state; its king had diplomatic and administrative relations with surrounding polities. David's flight to Gath — the home city of Goliath — is a desperate gamble: he is seeking refuge with the enemy whose champion he killed.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The servants of Achish recognize David: 'Is this not David the king of the land? Did they not sing of this one in the dances, Saul has struck his thousands, and David his ten thousands?' The victory song of 18:7 has traveled to Philistia — David's military reputation is known across the region. Being identified in an enemy court as 'king of the land' immediately threatens David's safety; the servants are alerting Achish to the political significance of the refugee.</p>",
    "12": "<p>David takes these words to heart and is very afraid of Achish the king of Gath. His fear is rational — he has been identified as Israel's de facto king by Achish's own servants. A foreign king who harbors a rival king's designated successor may be seen as a provocateur; worse, Achish might return David to Saul for political conciliation. David must immediately change how he is perceived.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David alters his behavior before them — acting as if he were insane, making marks on the doors of the gate and letting saliva run down his beard. Feigned madness as a self-protective stratagem was known in the ancient world: Odysseus feigned madness to avoid conscription for the Trojan War (Apollodorus, Epitome 3.7). In the ANE, madness was considered a divine affliction; harming a madman was considered an offense against the deity who had struck him. David is exploiting this religio-cultural protection by simulating divine judgment upon himself.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Achish says to his servants: 'Look, you see the man is mad. Why then have you brought him to me? Do I lack madmen, that you have brought this fellow to behave as a madman in my presence? Shall this fellow come into my house?' Achish's irritated dismissal achieves precisely what David needed: he is seen as harmlessly insane rather than as a political threat. The king's rhetorical question — 'do I lack madmen?' — suggests that the presence of madmen at court was not unusual (possibly as diviners or figures associated with divine judgment), but that importing a foreign one was pointless.</p>",
    "15": "<p>David departs from Gath to the cave of Adullam (22:1). The Gath episode ends with David's successful deception — he has extracted himself from a dangerous situation through wit rather than force. The Psalm headings of Pss 34 and 56 attribute them to this period; Ps 34 opens 'I will bless YHWH at all times; his praise shall continually be in my mouth' — the voice of a man who has just escaped what seemed like certain death through unexpected divine provision.</p>"
  }
}

